AUDIO: 'actually follows the prompt a lot more. It only generates two kids. And then here\'s another example, four children making two snowmen. After plugging it through Numina, it\'s able to fix the object counts as specified in the'

[24:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompt. Then here are some other examples. Now, this isn\'t just an issue with the older version of One. Even the top models out there like VEO 3.1 and Grok Imagine failed to generate the correct number of objects as specified'

[24:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the prompt. For example, for VEO 3.1, you can see that it generates four cyclists and a lot more than just three mountain goats. The awesome thing is Numina is model agnostic, so you can plug it into any open source model'

[24:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'including 1.2.1. So, here\'s an example of that as well as 1.2.2. The awesome thing is they\'ve released the code to this already. So, if you scroll up to the top of the page and you click on this code button, here it contains all'

[24:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the instructions on how to download and run this locally on your computer. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this page in the description below. Now, around 2 weeks ago, Google announces a crazy thing'

[24:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'called Turbo Quant, which is an AI memory compression algorithm that reduces the storage needed for large language models. So, that means you can fit huge models with smaller memory. It increases processing speeds by up to'

[25:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'eight times without losing much accuracy. Now, that was already a huge deal, but this week, we have an open-source option that\'s even better than Turbo Quant. So, this is called Rotor Quant, and this is also a'

[25:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'compression algorithm. Here it says it beats Google\'s Turbo Quant on every axis, including speed and quality and number of parameters. That\'s pretty insane. Now, this is quite technical,'

[25:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but I\'ll try to explain this in simple terms. You see, when a large language model generates text, it stores something called a KV cache, which basically remembers the key and value vectors for every token, so it can remember context. But, that memory grows'

[25:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fast. If your prompt becomes really long, if the context increases, then the KV cache can actually become the main thing eating up your GPU memory, not just the model itself. So, the key idea of Turbo Quant is what if we take these'

[26:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'KV vectors and rotate them into a nicer shape, and then compress them? Well, it works really well, but there\'s one catch. This rotation step is also expensive. It uses a big matrix'

[26:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'multiply, which costs a lot of compute. So, this new Rotor Quant asks, "What if we do the same thing, but way cheaper?" So, instead of one huge rotation across all dimensions, it breaks the vector into tiny chunks, just groups of three'

[26:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'numbers, and rotates each chunk independently using something called these Clifford rotators. And that\'s the change that makes it so fast. We\'re talking about taking Turbo Quant, which requires like 16,000 operations per'

[26:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'vector, down to around just 200. So, this gives you like over 10 times memory compression, making the decoding like 28% faster, the prefill to 5.3 times faster while using 44 times fewer'

[26:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parameters versus Google\'s Turbo Quant, which is already really good. So, this is a pretty insane compression algorithm. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this page in the description below. Also this'

[27:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'week, we have a new AI called MM-Fi video, and this is a framework which generates videos that are more physically realistic. The core idea here is simple. Instead of generating video'

[27:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'purely from pixels, it teaches the model actual physical understanding of a scene like motion, structure, and how objects interact. Because right now, basically video models only predict the next frame using pixels, and that\'s why you'

[27:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sometimes get some weird physics. Objects tend to warp or behave in strange ways. But, this framework tries to fix it by adding more signals into the model. So, if you compare this with like other video models like 1-2-1, you can see that this new MM-Fi video does'

[27:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look a lot more physically consistent. So, here\'s how it works. Think of it as giving the model multiple layers of data or reality. One layer is appearance, another one is for geometry, another one'

[27:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for motion, and so on. And then it trains them together as one system. It converts all of this into one unified format so the diffusion model can actually learn it and get a better understanding of physics. Now, if you scroll up to the top of the page here,'

